Iran on Film: A Forum on Culture, Politics and Daily life in Documentary Cinema, Kevorkian Center | NYU                                        NEW YORK UNIVERSITY       ARTS AND SCIENCE       COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE       GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                                                Back to  previous page                                  Iran on Film: A Forum on Culture, Politics and Daily life in Documentary Cinema     Since the 1979 Iranian Revolution, Americans’ exposure to Iran has   been largely limited to the news media’s portrayal of the nation’s   leadership, leaving many in the U.S. with little understanding of the   lives of ordinary Iranians. This event aims to offer a fuller portrait   of the country and its people through film, analysis, and discussion.   The event coincided with the release of the 2012 season of Link TV’s   ongoing “Bridge to Iran”   series, which aims to address the cultural differences and political   tensions that have developed between the Iran and the U.S. since the   1979 Iranian revolution. The series fills a knowledge gap by providing Americans with informed insider views on modern Iranian society, through documentaries made by Iranian directors living both inside Iran and within the Iranian diaspora. The series avoids simplistic categorizations and stereotypes about Iran to provide new insights and understandings of a nation, a people, and a culture that most Americans know little about. Find out more and watch films    Siah Bazi (2005) by Maryam Khakipour follows a well-known street theater troupe   Iran, A Cinematographic Revolution (2007) by Nader Takmil Homayoun explores contemporary Iran through its cinema  The Queen and I (2009) by Nahid Sarvestani documents the filmmaker’s uneasy encounters   with the former Queen of Iran  We are Half of Iran's Population (2009) by Rakshan Bani Etemad looks at women’s participation in   the controversial 2009 elections  A panel discussion featuring the following experts engaged with the   films alongside a discussion of the state and relevance of documentary   filmmaking on Iran from inside and outside the country. Iran on Film: A Forum on Culture, Politics and Daily life in Documentary Cinema, Kevorkian Center | NYU                                        NEW YORK UNIVERSITY       ARTS AND SCIENCE       COLLEGE OF ARTS AND SCIENCE       GRADUATE SCHOOL OF ARTS AND SCIENCE                                                Back to  previous page                                  Iran on Film: A Forum on Culture, Politics and Daily life in Documentary Cinema     Since the 1979 Iranian Revolution, Americans’ exposure to Iran has   been largely limited to the news media’s portrayal of the nation’s   leadership, leaving many in the U.S. with little understanding of the   lives of ordinary Iranians. This event aims to offer a fuller portrait   of the country and its people through film, analysis, and discussion.   The event coincided with the release of the 2012 season of Link TV’s   ongoing “Bridge to Iran”   series, which aims to address the cultural differences and political   tensions that have developed between the Iran and the U.S. since the   1979 Iranian revolution. The series fills a knowledge gap by providing Americans with informed insider views on modern Iranian society, through documentaries made by Iranian directors living both inside Iran and within the Iranian diaspora. The series avoids simplistic categorizations and stereotypes about Iran to provide new insights and understandings of a nation, a people, and a culture that most Americans know little about. Find out more and watch films    Siah Bazi (2005) by Maryam Khakipour follows a well-known street theater troupe   Iran, A Cinematographic Revolution (2007) by Nader Takmil Homayoun explores contemporary Iran through its cinema  The Queen and I (2009) by Nahid Sarvestani documents the filmmaker’s uneasy encounters   with the former Queen of Iran  We are Half of Iran's Population (2009) by Rakshan Bani Etemad looks at women’s participation in   the controversial 2009 elections  A panel discussion featuring the following experts engaged with the   films alongside a discussion of the state and relevance of documentary   filmmaking on Iran from inside and outside the country.
